  "market_context": "Daily oil chart from May 2023 to April 2024. Price had swept prior highs, formed bearish order blocks on the left side of the curve, then violated and retested those zones as mitigation blocks on the sell side. A fair value gap aligned with one mitigation block provided confluence for short entries.",
  "key_observation": "Old bearish order blocks (down-close candles) were dragged forward as mitigation blocks on the buy side; after price violated them, retests led to downward displacement, especially where confluenced with a fair value gap in discount.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified a bearish order block formed by down-close candles at ~68–72 (labeled 'Sell Side Liquidity' / 'Refill Liquidity') on the left side of the daily chart.",
    "Step 2: Noted price violated that order block with displacement upward, then retested it — expecting reaccumulation or redistribution in that zone.",
    "Step 3: Observed another bearish order block further left (down-close candles into a fair value gap), also violated and retested, forming a second mitigation block.",
    "Step 4: Highlighted confluence where a fair value gap aligned with a mitigation block near 79–83, creating a high-probability short setup zone in discount.",
    "Step 5: Confirmed short setups occurred when price swept a recent high, displaced down, and reacted at the mitigation block + FVG confluence."
  ],
  "outcome": "Short setups were taken in the mitigation block zones with FVG confluence; analyst stated 'we do get short setups in here' and was watching the order block as a live setup.",
  "lessons": "Mitigation blocks are old order blocks from the opposite side of the market maker curve, dragged forward for reaccumulation/redistribution. When violated and retested—especially with FVG or PD array confluence—they provide high-probability entries aligned with structure.",
